Considerable efforts have been devoted to the development of efficient ODH catalytic systems to improve the selectivity of olefin products, most of which used metal-based catalysts. These metal-based catalysts displayed high reactivity toward the oxidative conversion of alkanes but suffered from serious deep oxidation to COx, causing significant CO2 emission, owing to the strong interaction between the defected electrophilic metal sites and the electron-rich olefin products. The discovery of boron-based metal-free catalysts showed that this was well circumvented owing to the nucleophilicity of the metal-free catalysts that repelled the approach of olefins.
1.2 Scope of this review
In the past few decades, the research interest in the ODH reaction of light alkanes has been focused on catalytic systems of transition metal oxides (e.g., V2O5, MoO3, and NiO) and alkaline-earth metal oxychlorides.30,36,37 The recent discovery of a novel metal-free catalyst, functionalized hexagonal boron nitride (h-BN), with high activity and selectivity to olefins as well as negligible formation of CO2, represents a breakthrough in the development of the catalytic oxidative dehydrogenation reaction system.38,39 Subsequently, this new catalytic system attracted considerable research interest in the field of catalysis and material science. A series of boron-based catalysts have been synthesized with exceptional activity similar to h-BN, which paved a new route to selective cleavage of CH bonds.4049 In addition, nanocarbons were also reported to be active in ODH reactions, and have been used as a platform for the fundamental understanding of ODH reactions.5053 These metal-free catalytic systems offered alternative choices to industrialize ODH protocols, and nurtured a new growing point in the utilization of light alkanes as clean energy resources. Meanwhile, there is a quick advance in the understanding of the mechanistic issues, including active site, and the catalytic mechanism, to facilitate rational design of the ODH catalytic systems. A timely survey of the current status is highly necessary in order to promote future study. For this reason, we proceeded to write this review on the study of the metal-free boron- and carbon-based ODH catalytic systems, and overviewed the recent progress in the design of metal-free catalytic materials, and the essential reaction characteristics, including the identification of active sites and the fundamental understanding of the catalytic mechanism, to constitute a comprehensive view to share with the community. This article was finalized with a perspective on future directions in metal-free ODH catalysts. 2 Boron-based catalysts for ODH
2.1 Feature of boron-containing compounds
Boron occurred in nature predominantly as an oxyanion in minerals. It is a chameleon-like element, and may adopt various chemical environments, either as a backbone component to build two- or three-dimensional networks or as a doping atom to incorporate into zeolites and carbon materials, through which their surface electron densities, acid/base properties and functional groups can be modified to improve their performance in catalysis.
Owing to its moderate electronegativity (2.0 in Pauling scale), boron may form borides with metal or nonmetal elements. These, denoted as MmBn, are a family of binary compounds constituted by boron and less electronegative metal or nonmetal elements. They are normally prepared by the following methods: direct combination of the elements at high temperature; reduction of mixed oxides with active metals, carbon, or boron carbide; and reduction of metal oxide with boron.54,55 Borides are diverse in their structural morphologies and stoichiometries. For metal borides, they are classified roughly into boron-rich borides (B:M  4:1) and metal-rich borides (B:M < 4:1). The metal-rich borides contain isolated boron atoms, B2 pairs, boron chains or boron sheets. The structures of boron-rich borides are dominated by inter-boron bonding, and comprise three-dimensional networks of boron atoms and clusters in which the atoms of other elements occupy specific voids or vacant sites. Generally, most of the borides are extremely hard, chemically inert and involatile, and are usually used in high-temperature reactor vessels, crucibles, pump impellers and thermocouple sheaths.Its moderate electronegativity also enables boron to behave similar to carbon and silicon in its propensity to form covalently bound molecular compounds but with one less valence electron than the number of valence orbitals that they can form, a situation sometimes referred to as electron deficiency. This electron-deficient feature results in the complicated and fascinating properties of the compounds containing boron.5557 Its binary and ternary compounds with nonmetal elements, e.g. carbon, nitrogen, phosphorus, and oxygen, usually have similar physical properties and structural morphologies as metal borides.58,59 Boron oxide may breed various compounds by ready association with other elements, e.g. boric acid, borates, borosilicates,60 and boron phosphate.61,62 These compounds expanded the application of boron; for example, boron oxide and boric acid are widely used to prepare borates and other boron-containing materials, and borate has important applications in mineralogy, nonlinear optical materials, laser materials and catalysis. In these oxygenated compounds, boron may adopt two coordination modes, trigonal BO3 and BO4 tetrahedra (B2O6 units), which are generally neighbored to each other via a common vertex or edge to form BxOy polyanion clusters with various configurations.63,64Scheme 1 shows a typical structure of boron-based materials used as ODH catalysts.Scheme 1 Schematic elucidation of typical boron-based materials used as ODH catalysts: (a) edge-hydroxylated boron nitride (BNOH);39 Reproduced from ref. 39 with permission from the Wiley-VCH, copyright 2017. (b) BN nanotubes (BNNTs);65 Reproduced from ref. 65 with permission from the Royal Society of Chemistry, copyright 2016. (c) Spherical superstructure of hexagonal boron nitride;47 Reproduced from ref. 47 with permission from the American Chemical Society, copyright 2015. (d) Boron carbide;66 Reproduced from ref. 66 with permission from the Wiley-VCH, copyright 2018. (e) B2O3/SBA-15.44 Reproduced from ref. 44 with permission from the American Chemical Society, copyright 2015.
2.2 Binary boron-based catalysts
2.2.1 Hexagonal boron nitride Boron nitrides (BN) may exist in three crystalline forms: graphite-like hexagonal BN (h-BN), diamond-like cubic BN (c-BN), and wurtzite BN (w-BN).65 Under standard conditions, h-BN with a layered structure analogous to graphite is the most stable BN phase.65 With the development of modern technology, h-BN has been synthesized through many methods, such as mechanical or chemical exfoliation, chemical vapor deposition (CVD), and solid-state reactions, and has been extensively used in electronics (wide bandgap (5.06.0 eV)), optics (no optical absorption in 390700 nm) and thermotics (high thermal conductivity 33 W m1 K1) benefitted from its excellent physical properties.67,68 In the field of heterogeneous catalysis, h-BN is generally considered to be chemically inert over the years and has been merely employed as a support in various reaction systems, such as ammonia synthesis,69,70 CO oxidation,71 selective oxidation,7275 and FischerTropsch synthesis.76 Besides, Bao et al. designed coreshell nanocatalysts by an encapsulation strategy and confirmed the confinement effect of h-BN shells that could stabilize the active metal components with an enhanced activity and stability for syngas methanation.77 Beyond that, investigation concerning its catalytic activity is scarce.78
Breakthrough was made when the Hermans group38 and Lu group39 independently reported their finding in the highly specific reactivity of h-BN in catalyzing the ODH of propane. Hermans and co-workers38 reported a selectivity of 79% for propylene and 12% for ethylene at 14% propane conversion in the h-BN catalytic system, which ran stably for over 32 h, with a COx proportion of 9%, a value far lower than that produced over traditional VOx/SiO2 catalysts at 9% propane conversion (Fig. 2a).38 Similar product distributions were observed when using BNNTs, but with a higher rate of propylene productivity (kgC3H6 kgcat1 h1) than h-BN by more than five times (Fig. 2b).
