Lu and coworkers39 reported more pronounced performance of home-made edge-hydroxylated boron nitride (BNOH) in the ODH of propane and ethane to the corresponding olefins with high selectivity and negligible CO2 formation, on which high propane conversion (20.6%) and olefin selectivity (80.2% for C3 and 90.9% for C23) were achieved with considerably low CO2 formation (0.5%) (Fig. 2c). Meanwhile, feeding propylene and molecular oxygen did not consume propylene, demonstrating the suppression of its over-oxidation in the BNOH catalytic system. BNOH also exhibited olefin productivity of 6.8 golefin gcat1 h1, which was far higher than those of metal oxide catalysts, and remained stable for at least 300 h (Fig. 2d).
In the ODH of ethane on BNOH,42 the ethylene selectivity reached up to 95%, 90%, and 80% at the ethane conversion of 11%, 40%, and 63%, respectively, with only a negligible amount of CO2 (Fig. 3a). These results show that the BNOH catalyzed ODH is comparable to the industrialized ethane steam cracking process in view of their ethylene selectivity (85% at 60% ethane conversion for the latter), but wins over the latter considering the much lower reaction temperature and CO2 emission.79 The BNOH catalyst can also afford high ethylene productivity (9.1 gC2H4 gcat1 h1) with >90% selectivity by modulating the reaction conditions (Fig. 3b). The remarkable stability of the BNOH catalyst was evidenced by the operation for 200 h at 590 C (Fig. 3c). Such stable productivity far exceeded the critical value, 1 gC2H4 gcat1 h1, and demonstrated its potential application for industry.36 Fig. 3 ODH of ethane on h-BN:42 (a) dependence of ethane conversion, ethylene selectivity and yield on the reaction temperature; (b) effect of space velocity and reaction temperature on the productivity of ethylene. (c) Long-term stability test at 590 C. Reproduced from ref. 42 with permission from the Elsevier Ltd, copyright 2017.
By means of various advanced experimental characterization techniques and computational methods, the determining role of edge BOH groups was identified unambiguously,39,42 which represented a distinct understanding with that reported.38 The comparative study40 on the catalytic activity of several boron-containing compounds (B4C, Ti2B, NiB, CoxB, HfB2, and WB) and elemental B in ODH also confirmed the importance of BO sites and showed that the absence of nitrogen sites did not eliminate the catalytic activity of boron-containing compounds. The knowledge on the responsible species in the h-BN catalytic systems has since then been evolving, and it is now a consensus38,39,42,78,8083 that oxygenated boron species dictate the performance of the boron-based catalysts.
The suppression of over-oxidation of alkanes on h-BN was also demonstrated by the ODH reactions of n-butane and isobutane,84 in which the main side products were observed to be C2 and C3 olefins rather than COx. In contrast, the main side product was COx in the Cr-based,85,86 V-based,87 and P modified CNT50 catalytic systems at similar alkane conversion levels. The total selectivity of all formed olefins (ethylene, propylene, butylene, and isobutylene) on the h-BN catalyst was over 85% at 10% alkane conversion. This also showed that h-BN may be used in n-butane oxidative cracking to produce ethylene and propylene by decreasing the presence of O2 to shift the dominant product distribution from butylenes (oxidative dehydrogenation products) to propylene and ethylene (cracking products), which may be further enhanced at elevated reaction temperature with high selectivity for propylene (43.9%) and ethylene (24.2%), and the catalytic system remained stable for over 100 h with low total COx selectivity (1.2%).88 Hexagonal boron nitride is known with the low presence of defects. Accordingly, an option to further optimize its catalytic performance would be to increase the number of active sites. High surface area boron nitride nanosheets synthesized by the reaction of boric acid with urea were reported to show high activity for ODH of ethane with nearly 100% selectivity for ethylene at 10% conversion of ethane, which changed to 60% if raising the ethane conversion to 78% during which the catalytic system remained stable for at least 400 h at 575 C.41 When using dicyanamide to substitute for urea in the preparation for high surface area boron nitride,43 its enhanced catalytic performance was maintained in the ODH of propane in view of the 53% propylene selectivity and 18% ethylene selectivity at a 52% propane conversion. However, the operation time of this catalytic system was measured to be only about 5 h, owing to the oxidation of surface BN bonds in the oxidative atmosphere, which may be improved by the addition of ammonia to more than 100 h. Ball-milled h-BN can expose more edge sites with significantly increased surface area, leading to a significant improvement in view of the ethylene selectivity (92%) at 10% ethane conversion in ODH of ethane compared to pristine h-BN (42%).89 The third way to increase the number of active sites is via nanostructural engineering by assembling 2D h-BN into a 3D spherical superstructure. This catalyst afforded a selectivity of 78% for propylene and 10% for ethylene at the propane conversion of 20% in the ODH of propane and operated for 100 h at 490 C, and increasing the temperature to 510 C resulted in high conversion of propane of 58% but bifurcated olefin selectivity (48% for propylene and 21% for ethylene).47 This study also showed that this morphology lowered the apparent activation energy to 175.3 kJ mol1, implicating that lower energy channels were favored on this catalyst.
The preparation of a boron nitride wash-coated monolithic catalyst49 offered an applicable way to improve, besides the olefin selectivity, the heat and mass transfer which is vital for industrialization owing to the intrinsic feature of high exothermicity of the ODH reaction that could produce hotspots and thus subsequent negative consequences in the olefin selectivity and safety issues. This h-BN wash-coated cordierite monolithic catalyst was fabricated by chemical vapor deposition using boric acid and urea as precursors, and exhibited 82.1% propylene selectivity with only 3.7% CO and no detected CO2 at 16.8% propane conversion in the ODH of propane with high gas hourly space velocity (GHSV, 576000 mL gBN1 h1) (Fig. 4a). The well-developed straight-channel and short diffusive pathway of the thin wash-coated h-BN layer guaranteed the mass transfer process at high GHSV, and achieved a high propylene productivity of 18.6 gC3H6 gBN1 h1, both of which are critical indicators for the potential industrial implementation of ODH.49 Fig. 4 High space velocity and low risk of hotspot formation in the propane ODH over h-BN: (a) effect of space velocities and reaction temperatures on the propane conversion and product selectivity over the h-BN/Cordierite catalyst. Black square denotes C3H8 conversion, whereas bars represent product selectivity;49 Reproduced from ref. 49 with permission from the Elsevier Ltd, copyright 2018. (b) The temperature gradients of VOx/γ-Al2O3 and h-BN-C catalyst beds with different tube diameters at the same GHSV.90 Reproduced from ref. 90 with permission from the Elsevier Ltd, copyright 2018.
The presence of hotspots in the catalyst bed is a typical phenomenon in the ODH of light alkanes owing to its highly exothermic nature, which can significantly accelerate the undesired over-oxidation of olefins, leading to a low selectivity to olefins. It is a consensus that the catalyst design is one of the two key components in an industrial implementation, with another one the reactor engineering, and an ideal strategy is determined by their optimal synergy.9 Boron nitride materials are known with high thermal conductivity (33 W m1 K1), and thus are ideal choices to remove quickly the heat generated in ODH reactions, which is crucial to the industrialization of the ODH protocol. A recent computational fluid dynamics (CFD) simulation compared the hotspot and the temperature profiles in the fixed-bed reactor in the ODH of propane using h-BN and VOx/γ-Al2O3 as catalysts, respectively,90 and showed that the temperature of the catalyst bed increased by less than 1 C in the h-BN catalyst bed which was much smaller than that in the VOx/γ-Al2O3 catalyst bed (8 C) at a similar propane conversion (25%) with a micro-tubular reactor of 6 mm in diameter. The high thermal conductivity of an h-BN catalyst could maintain isothermal operation in such a micro-tubular reactor at even up to 590 C with a higher propane conversion of 45%. In contrast, a hotspot of >5 C temperature gradient was inevitable in the VOx/γ-Al2O3 catalyst bed even at the relatively low temperature of 520 C. In an industrially relevant reactor with an inner diameter of 60 mm, the h-BN catalyst bed maintained a uniform temperature profile (a temperature gradient as small as 1.5 C), while the VOx/γ-Al2O3 catalyst bed suffered from a temperature gradient of 47 C (Fig. 4b). These results suggest that the superior thermal conductivity the h-BN catalyst favors its industrial practice in ODH of light alkanes conducted in a fixed-bed reactor.
The investigation of the influence of reactor parameters on the ODH of propane using the h-BN catalyst showed91 that there was little transport limitation, and the use of SiC as an inert catalyst diluent may promote the catalysis significantly. This work attributed this to the contribution of the surface-initiated gas phase radical reactions, which is different from the opinion in the CFD simulation90 that emphasized the known high thermal conductivity of the catalyst. In this work, the authors reported a volcano-like dependence of the propane consumption rate on the mass of h-BN. This may be the consequence of multiple reasons, e.g. the contribution of gas-phase radical chemistry that did not rely on the quantity of the catalyst, the forming and encapsulation of the catalyst, and other issues, which remain to be clarified.
2.2.2 Silicon boride Silicon borides have a number of phases with a stoichiometric ratio of B:Si ranging from 3 to 6 with complicated morphologies varied from homogeneity to heterogeneity.9294 According to a crystallographic study, the unit cell of SiB6 contains 289 atoms with 281 of them building up interconnected icosahedra (18) and icosihexahedra (4).95 Silicon borides are generally synthesized by melting a certain proportion of elemental silicon and boron at high temperature and pressure, and adjusting the temperature and the ratio of B/Si may result in their various phases.
Silicon borides are widely used as substrates in the synthesis of ceramic composite96 and borosilicate glass materials,97 or as an additive in the modification of carbon fibre/lithium aluminosilicate composites.98 They are also used as an antioxidant coating material taking advantage of the facile formation of an oxide film on their surface, showing their good oxidation resistance at high temperatures.99,100 Though rarely used in catalysis, their rich boron sites and good oxidation resistance endow them as potential catalysts to promote ODH of light alkanes. In a recent study, oxygenated silicon borides were prepared with SiB6 as the main phases and remarkable catalytic performance was observed in ODH of light alkanes including ethane (95.8% C2 at 29% ethane conversion, and 90% C2 at 50% conversion), propane (82.2% C3 at 19% propane conversion, and 88.7% C23 at 31% propane conversion) and isobutane (77.1% C4 and 96.4% C24 at 6% isobutane conversion, and 90.9% C24 at 15.6% isobutane conversion),45 showing superior performance in resisting over-oxidation of olefins at high conversion (Fig. 5). In addition, the light olefin productivity was up to 1.22.6 golefins gcat1 h1, and the silicon boride catalyst in the ODH of propane remained stable for more than 100 h.45 Note that most silicon boride materials have relatively low specific surface areas, and the synthesis of silicon boride with high specific surface may be an effective way to improve its catalytic activity.
