2.2.3 Boron carbide Boron carbide (B410.4C) is a compositionally disordered material with rhombohedral phase.101,102 The primary structural units of boron carbide are the 12-atom icosahedra located at the vertices of a rhombohedral lattice of trigonal symmetry, and the 3-atom linear chains that link the icosahedra along the (111) rhombohedral axis (Fig. 6a and b).103 Since it was reported in 1883, various protocols for its synthesis have been developed, including magnesiothermic reduction, carbothermic reduction, vapor phase reactions, synthesis from elements and synthesis from polymer precursors,101 to produce boron carbide with distinct morphologies (Fig. 6c and d), e.g. thin films via direct ion-beam deposition and plasma-enhanced chemical vapor deposition from boranes,104,105 nanorods by reacting carbon nanotubes (CNTs) with boron powder, the boron carbide nanoparticles that can be synthesized by reacting multiwall CNT with magnesium diboride at high temperature in a vacuum or an inert atmosphere,106,107 bulk boron carbide by the reaction of boric acid and polyvinyl alcohol at low temperature,108 and fine powder, fibers, whiskers and thin film coating of boron carbide101 by vapor phase reactions.
