Owing to its superior properties such as high hardness (29.1 GPa), high melting point (2450 C), high elastic modulus (448 GPa) and chemical inertness, B4C is widely applied in wear-resistant materials, vehicle armor, and strengthening medium. Furthermore, B4C can also be used as a nuclear reactor, neutron detector and shielding material,111,112 owing to its capability to absorb neutrons without forming long-lived radionuclides.
In recent years, boron carbide has been used in catalysis as a support in methanol oxidation113 and proton exchange membrane (PEM) fuel cells114 to load Pt catalysts or directly participated in catalyzed oxidative desulfurization for ultra-deep desulfurization.115 Its activity in catalyzing oxidative ODH reactions was also reported40 displaying the same catalytic behavior as h-BN in ODH of propane with an alkane consumption rate of 4.7 × 103 molC3H8 kgcat1 s1 at 500 C and remaining stable for 2 days (Fig. 6e).
2.2.4 Boron oxide Boron oxide (B2O3) with low melting point (450 C) and low viscosity (436 Poise at 750 C) is mainly found in the vitreous form116 featuring a random three-dimensional network of BO3-triangles with a comparatively high fraction of six-membered rings (boroxol rings) and a portion of non-ring BO3/2 units,117119 with the boroxol rings decaying in the liquid state with increasing temperature.120 Due to its low melting point of boron oxide and its dispersion behavior, when used in catalysis, it is often used as a supported catalyst, e.g. on Al2O3, ZrO2, TiO2, SiO2, MgO and zeolites,121125 and it has been reported to be active in the Beckmann rearrangement of cyclohexanone oxime,126 cyclohexene hydrogen transfer reaction,127 disproportionation of toluene and isomerization reaction.128 The supported boron oxide catalysts consist of tri-coordinated BO3 species and tetra-coordinated BO4 species, and the proportion of tetra-coordinated BO4 species is closely related to the enhanced Brnsted acidity when increasing the amount of loaded boron oxide.129,130 The morphology of the loaded boron oxide may be manipulated by vapor decomposition of B(OEt)3 onto silica gel126 to produce more active sites and uniformly distributed acidic sites for improved catalytic performance compared to the ordinary impregnation method using H3BO3. Unsupported boron oxide was rarely reported in catalysis.131
Owing to the exothermic feature of alkane oxidation, when used in the partial oxidation and ODH of light alkane, boron oxide was prepared in its supported form to avoid its leakage. In earlier studies, supported boron oxide catalysts on metal oxides (Al2O3, MgO, La2O3, ZnO, etc.) were prepared132,133 for the partial oxidation of ethane, where the B2O3(30 wt%)/Al2O3 exhibited the best catalytic performance in the production of acetaldehyde (selectivity: 2.7%, yield: 1.03%) and ethylene (selectivity: 58.0%, yield: 14.6%) with an ethane conversion of 38.0% at 550 C, but at the cost of emission of a large amount of CO (selectivity: 31.0%). The active site for the initial activation of ethane (CH bond cleavage) was suggested to be crystalline B2O3, but that for further oxidation to acetaldehyde could be different from the formation of ethylene. Similarly, Auroux et al.134 synthesized an alumina-boria catalyst by chemical vapor deposition and obtained more dispersed boron oxide on the support surface for ethane selective oxidation. The highest activity was observed with 30 wt% boron oxide loading on non-porous Al2O3 where the ethylene yield was 16.7% at 18.7% ethane conversion. CO and CH4 were the main by-products, coming from the decomposition of ethylene. Later, Buyevskaya et al.135137 reported selective oxidation of propane to olefins and oxygenates on supported boron oxide catalysts. The highest selectivity of propylene was 42% at 30% propane conversion on B2O3/Al2O3; in addition, the selectivity of C1C3 oxygenates was up to 28%. The trigonal BO3 species present in both crystalline and amorphous phases are active in the dehydrogenation of propane to propylene, and oxygenate formation was favored in the presence of Al6B8O21 phase. The above-mentioned alumina-boria catalysts also displayed catalytic activity for partial oxidation of light alkanes. However, for ODH of light alkanes to olefins, there still existed a significant amount of deep oxidation products, such as oxygenates, CO and CO2, due to the strong acidic sites generated by depositing boron oxide on amphoteric alumina. Besides, the leaching of boron under reaction conditions led to the instability of boron oxide catalysts.
These supported boron oxide catalysts are deficient in common in the nonnegligible deep oxidation. This is most possibly due to the supports which are intrinsically active to catalyze the oxidation of alkanes.
2.2.4.1 Boron oxide supported on silica In order to remove the influence of the support and figure out the origin of the catalytic ability of boron oxide, Lu's group44 reported a supported boron oxide catalyst synthesized by incipient wetness impregnation of boric acid on the high specific area mesoporous silica (B2O3/SBA-15, denoted as BOS catalyst) which showed remarkable selectivity to catalyze the ODH of propane. The BOS catalyst contained four types of boron species (Fig. 7a and b), i.e. boroxol ring (B(3a)), tri-coordinated hydroxylated linear BO3/2 (B(3b)), and tri-coordinated planar boron species (B(3c)) and a tetra-coordinated tetrahedral boron species (B(4)) which were fused into the silica matrix. This catalyst was active at a temperature as low as 405 C, which is about 100 C lower than that of the BN catalyst, showing a propane conversion of 2.8% and a propylene selectivity of 84.1% (C23: 94.6%). Increasing the temperature to 450 C raised the propane conversion to 14.8% with a selectivity of 73.3% for propylene and 87.4% for both propylene and ethylene (C23), and the BOS catalyst was stable during the 30 hours operation at 450 C. Both experimental and theoretical studies indicated that tri-coordinated boroxol ring and hydroxylated linear boron species were the active sites responsible for the low temperature activity and high efficiency in catalyzing ODH of light alkanes. A study138 of the same catalytic system reported consistent results, in which similar responsible oxygenated boron species were proposed (Fig. 7c) and a selectivity of 77% for propylene and of 91% for overall olefin (C23) corresponding to a propane conversion of 5% at 500 C were obtained (Fig. 7d).
