2.3 Ternary boron-based catalyst: boron phosphate
Boron phosphate (BPO4) has superior thermal stability, high thermal conductivity (ka = 62.4 W m1 K1, kc = 51.5 W m1 K1), strong anisotropic thermal expansion and outstanding oxidation resistance.172175 The crystal structure of BPO4 is featured by a continuous three-dimensional framework composed of corner-sharing BO4 and PO4 tetrahedra (Fig. 9a), isomorphous with α-quartz or β-cristobalite.176179 BPO4 is usually synthesized from precursors H3PO4 and H3BO3, B2O3 and (NH4)2HPO4, or B2O3 and P2O5 at a temperature ranging from 80 to 1200 C.180,181 Other methods e.g. solvothermal synthesis,182,183 top-seeding flux growth184,185 and microwave-assisted methods,181 were also reported.
Fig. 9 Structure and performance of BPO4 in propane ODH: (a) crystalline BPO4; 186 (b) 2D view of BPO4;186 Reproduced from ref. 186 with permission from the Wiley-VCH, copyright 2017. (c) TEM image of ordered macroporous BPO4;200 (d) comparison for BPO4 and several representative catalysts;200 Reproduced from ref. 200 with permission from the Elsevier Ltd, copyright 2020. (e) SEM images of B2O3@BPO4;48 (f) long-term catalytic performance of B2O3@BPO4.48 Reproduced from ref. 48 with permission from the Elsevier Ltd, copyright 2019.
Benefitting from the coexistence of Brnsted and Lewis acidic sites (Fig. 9b),186 BPO4 manifested itself as an effective solid acid catalyst in organic reactions, such as dehydration,187,188 oligomerization,189 decomposition,190,191 Beckmann rearrangement,192 and alkylation.193 In the study194 of selective dehydration of 1,2-propanediol to propanal by the evaporation method, BPO4 exhibited more durable activity and offered a higher yield of propanal over 95% at low temperature than conventional solid acid catalysts. It was also supported on silica by chemical vapor deposition using a mixture of boron triethoxide and phosphoryl trimethoxide and used in the isomerization of 1-butylene and simultaneous oligomerization of 1-butane.195 In an earlier study,196199 mixed oxides of boron and phosphorus were reported to show activity in the partial oxidation of light alkanes (CH4, C2H6, and C3H8), with high conversion of light alkanes and a wide spectrum of oxygenated products. When the C3H8 conversion approached 53%, the selectivity of C3-oxygenates, C3H6, C2 + C1 oxygenates and CO was 8.1%, 31.7%, 10.4% and 26.7%, respectively. In the CH4 or C2H6 partial oxidation, the selectivity of HCHO and CH3CHO could be obtained as high as 13.7% and 14.2%. In these studies, olefin products did not present as major products, showing that the responsible species in the catalytic system favored mono-oxygen insertion into the CH and CC bonds more than dehydrogenation of the alkane substrates. Note that these studies did not characterize the structure of the catalyst and it is unknown whether the mixed oxides were BPO4 or something else. It is worth carrying out an extensive study to solve these puzzles.
It is known that the preparation of BPO4 crystals often requires high temperature and produces bulk solids with low surface areas. This in general disfavors the exposure of active sites and the maximization of surface area. Methods developed to tackle this issue include the creation of ordered microporous morphology in the bulk of BPO4200 or loading it onto a support. In a recent work, in order to improve the exposure of active sites and the mass transfer, a three-dimensional ordered macroporous BPO4 material was developed200 with a robust framework (Fig. 9c), which exhibited excellent activity and selectivity in the ODH of propane with a selectivity of 91.5% for olefins (propylene: 82.5%, ethylene: 9.0%) at a propane conversion of 14.3% at 515 C and a selectivity for the unwanted deep-oxidized CO2 product of less than 1.0%. Furthermore, the catalyst exhibited a remarkable olefin productivity of 16 golefin gcat1 h1, which well outperformed most ODH catalysts (Fig. 9d).
BPO4 was also used as a support in ODH catalytic systems. A B2O3@BPO4 sandwich-like hollow sphere (Fig. 9e) was reported as a liquid-phase catalyst in ODH of propane,48 and remained stable for 27 h at 550 C with a C3H6 productivity of 0.79 gC3H6 gcat1 h1 and a selectivity of 66.4% for propylene and 18.4% for ethylene at a propane conversion of 24.7%. The loaded B2O3 was proposed in its molten state and worked as the active species, as in previous work of boron-containing catalytic systems, and BPO4 acted not only as a support, but also as a cocatalyst in the reaction.48 Compared to the performance of other boron-based ODH catalysts, this material remains to be improved in its operation stability and olefin productivity (Fig. 9f).
